snippet.textDisplay:
My first impressions are:

1) I love the mood of it, the lovely instrumentation and the free-floating time feel. It has a "timeless" quality to it in more ways than one.

2) I'm digging Dylan's vocal delivery, switching naturally and effortlessly between singing and speaking voices, and moving easily, loosely and confidently with the instrumental accompaniment.

3) It's an extended cornucopia of specific cultural references which I'm about 99% familiar with, being a 62-year-old American who's paid close attention to the various historical strains of the nation's music, and observed its politics and social realities over the course of time. I know that many younger listeners won't get a lot of the references. But that's OK, cause Dylan isn't singing it for them. Or, he *is*, if they're the kind of young people who'd listen carefully and start googling!

4) It strikes me as a masterful collage of images and ideas, brought together to bump up against each other in unexpected ways. Another appropriate metaphor from visual art would be a mosaic, I think. All these disparate bits, put together to form, well, an historical tale, in poetic form. And a kind of summation, a sort of final tying up of the era of JFK (and much of what preceded it, and some of that which has followed) into a bundle, and placing it on our table, as a gift, to unwrap and consider anew.

snippet.textDisplay:
I hadn't realized the impact of JFK 's assassination on the world scene, until I was a young teenager in the early eighties...when an elderly Cretan shephard recalled where he was on that day when he got the news and how emotional he became reliving that moment.
Up until then, I thought only Americans suffered the loss of this president. It's been amazing to discover how many foreigners that I've met through the years can remember exactly what they were doing on "that" day.
Thank you Mr. Dylan.
